segments.text: Did you go to the Baptist Church your first year?
That's when I was living in town.
And we went to First Baptist Church downtown.
I see.
First Baptist Church in O'Brien.
And then the second year?
When I moved out onto the campus, we went to the First Baptist Church in College Station.
Were there Sunday night activities for college students?
Not necessarily.
They were just pretty general activities.
And about, did many students go to church?
I don't recall a whole bunch did.
Actually, the pastor at the First Baptist Church was our guy who married us.
Ah.
So you married a Baptist?
Yes.
Well, really, she was a Methodist when we got married, and she joined the Baptist Church.
Well, you converted her.
Yeah.
I guess God did that.
Let's see.
There weren't any girls on the campus.
When the war was over and the students came back, do you remember that it was any...
Did, were the courses harder or easier?
Did you have to study any more?
Well, actually, I think probably before I probably would take, say, 16, 18 hours.
But in my senior year, it seemed like I had 21 hours.
You know, so it seemed to have been easier to come by than it was before.
Do you remember who you turned to after the war for any advice?
If you needed academic advice or counseling?
Well, not officially, I'd say.
But unofficially, who'd you go to see?
Well, this man in economics that I couldn't remember his name, he and I were more like friends than student and teacher.
And where was economics in those days?
Was it in Nagel Hall?
I don't recall that an academic building is where everything was taken care of.
Most of that type of course was handled in an academic building.
Let's see.
Some of the A&M traditions.
Do you remember when you first went to a Silver Taps event?
Well, I can remember going to one, but I don't remember when.
Was it before the war or after?
It seemed like it was after the war.
And we went out and stood in front of an academic building in the middle of the night.
And it was a rather solemn time.
What were your feelings as you walked back to your room?
I can't remember.
Did you by chance go to that famous 1946 muster when Eisenhower spoke?
April 21, 1946, General Eisenhower came here to speak, and they had some of the survivors of the Corregidor muster.
No, I didn't attend that.
I'm sure I would have remembered.
But I think they did it over at the MSC, did they not?
I think so.
Out there in front?
I think so.
In the drill field?
I think so.
But see, since you weren't in the Corps, you didn't go through final review.
When did you get your senior ring?
I think before I went into service, I think I was already a classified junior.
I can't remember exactly.
But anyway, you don't make rings like this anymore.
You know, this is a 14-karat thing.
And all my...
insignia is practically worn off.
And I thought about sending it back in, but it wouldn't have the same connotation anymore.
And what class are you?
Class of 44.
44, okay.
I got out in 47.
Yes, sir, I understand.
But I still have my class of 44.
I think that's, you start off from your freshman year, you count that one.
How much did that ring cost?
Seemed like $37.
Do you have any good ring stories?
Well, when I first came down here, I had a friend from up in Collin County, and he and I were close.
And he was already a junior, and he used to let me wear his ring.
It was unofficial, you know, because you're not supposed to let anybody wear the ring.
It doesn't earn it.
Did...
Did you ever lose your ring?
Yes.
I didn't lose it for long, but I lost it.
We'd been on a trip to see my family up in North Texas, and that's when the roads up there were two-lane roads and went through the country, you know.
And so I was wearing my ring.
We was coming home in the morning from my sister's house down one of these country roads, and my ring got pretty onerous.
You sweat out of there, and it burned and everything, so...
I was trying to get it off while I was driving, so I was pushing on it like this.
And this car, the cars out there had this little vents, you know, on the side.
And I pushed that thing off and it bounced around on the dashboard and flew out the window.
And we were doing probably 50, 60 miles an hour.
So, boy, I stopped and I didn't know how far down the road I had driven.
But we drove back and the boys were, you know, within five and six or something like that.
So I said, I got to find that ring.
So there's not much traffic on that road.
So all of us were walking up and down and over on the side was a plowed field, you know, and on the other side was a plowed field.
And so we walked along there for about 30 minutes and nobody found the ring.
So I said to my wife, well, we just, not like,
We're not ever going to find it.
Maybe somebody sent it to me and looked my name in there.
So I guess I'm going to walk right down here, and if I don't find that ring along somewhere down that way, we're going to have to go.
So I walked down as far as I thought I should go.
I turned around to go back, and I stepped on my ring.
Oh, good, good.
Not in the middle of the road, man.
Have you ever been somewhere unusual and somebody recognized it?
I do that all the time.
My wife's in a nursing home, incidentally.
And they have little people come in, you know, not employees or anything, but maybe from the church or someplace.
And so I was walking through the lobby one day, and there's two little girls there.
One of them said, oh, there's a naggy!

very good for real for any all of a sudden you know and that happens lots of times are you a graduate A&M no sir i went to austin college undergraduate and rice my phd is that a rice ring yes no that's an austin college ring oh it is
And I'm sorry that at many schools today, rings are now old-fashioned.
At many colleges, the kids don't buy rings anymore.
They think that's out of date.
Yeah, and I think it's splendid.
What are the things that build Aggie pride?
What makes Aggies so proud of this institution?
Well, we get the cream of the crop students, for one thing.
And then there's just the loyalties, a bond between guys on the campus.
What builds that bond?
What creates it?
Love, I think.
The guys have learned to love each other.
And I had a friend, a boy I loved with all my might and main.
He was 10 years my junior.
But
He and I got along pretty good.
And his family lived out here in a little town called Snook.
And it was too far for me to go home every weekend, so he'd take me home with him.
And I got to know his family.
His family's similar to mine.
My family's seven girls and four boys.
And they had six girls and five boys.
And I just fit it in out there.
He died about six months ago.
He had emphysema.
He quit smoking, they said.
He lived down close to Houston.
I didn't see him anymore.
His sister-in-law told me that he got emphysema, but she said it was too late.
If you get emphysema, don't go away.
He was on oxygen and everything, and his first wife,
And I and he were like brother and sister.
They were younger than I, but we just had a rapport.
But she died with cancer too, so.
then he got married again.
It's just a girl that's 21 years younger than him.
And they wouldn't, his sister-in-law, who might have been a little prejudiced, said she wouldn't let him see any of his family or nothing.
She wanted him just for herself.
When you were in the Air Force, what had you learned here as an Aggie that,
proved to be important while you were on active duty?
Well, being discreet, maybe.
You know, you learn things at A&M, you know, about loyalty and that sort of thing that you carry over to military.
And I was real happy with my military years.
Did you, was it good to be an Aggie?
Did sometimes that help you?
We had Aggie meetings in
in London, you know, on those days when they had these things, you know, the aprils.
Y'all had a muster?
Yeah.
Really?
There wasn't very many of us.
There was five or six of us there, but they had a muster in London.
Very good.
I got permission from my captain, you know, the commander, to attend it.
Did you attend muster when you came back from the war?
Yes, I did.
Occasionally.
I didn't make all of them, you know, but
I tried to be among those present.
It's hard to get a place to stand when you try to go to muster here.
And then sometimes you forget or something.
I don't make them regularly.
One of the questions I thought of, I forgot to ask you a while ago about the Aggieland Orchestra.
Did you all have an opening and a closing theme song?
The Aggieland Orchestra?
Oh, I don't believe so.
I don't remember.
We might have had a Good Night song.
What was it?
Do you know?
Well, let's see.
Good night, my love.
The tired old moon is descending.
I believe that was the one we used all the time.
There was another one that was similar to it, but I don't recall that we ever used that one.
What did you all open with?
Just maybe something jazzy.
Get everybody in the mood.
And how often did you introduce a new song?
Well, not too often.
We had a really big library.
And we had most of those songs that were popular in that era.
And so we just pretty much stayed with that thing.
And you said you all practiced about once a week.
Where did you practice?
In Spica.
That's where the piano was.
Oh.
Something.
Was that Mother's?
We're getting near the end.
As you were getting ready to graduate, how well prepared did you think A&M had made you for the real world?
Well, I thought I always wanted a college degree.
And when I was graduating from high school, I went over to Denton.
I thought maybe I could get a job over there as a musician.
But that school was not big enough to have very many bands or anything there, and the one that they had was already filled.
So I didn't meet with any success, but that didn't light my desire for a higher education, and particularly one at A&M.
I had met A&M's junior, not junior, freshman baseball team.
They came to McKinney and played the line.
And I got acquainted with all of them, as a matter of fact, but a particular one of them, a freshman.
And he encouraged me to go to A&M.
He strengthened my desire to go to A&M.
And I had always wanted to.
And when I had a chance to come to A&M, I cast aside a lot of things that would keep me from going to A&M.
And I came down here, like I told Murray, when he said, I don't know whether you ought to come down here or not.
I said, well, I'm here and I'm going to stay.
What are the key ingredients of an Aggie?
Well, most of them are mentally and spiritually mature, you know.
And I haven't met
I'm not going to say how many Aggies that I didn't approve of, you know.
Most of them, even now, I'll meet somebody I've never seen before.
He said, Aggie, and he means you've got a rapport with them, you know.
I don't know what it is.
As long as there was no girls here and just a corps, you know, you got allied with your roommate and all the group, and you were in an organization
You had to be in an organization.
I don't know.
There's just something about nagging.
You meet a guy that's a nagging, and immediately you line up with him, you know.
And I'm just happy that I had that chance to come to A&M.
When you were a student, did you ever help gather up the stuff for Bonfire?
No, I didn't.
I was
particularly done by the Corps members.
And it was a really unfortunate thing that they had there in November.
Oh, yes, yes.
Now, I understand before the war that usually it was just trash.
Yes, mostly, you know, it was picked up somewhere.
I think they might have had a source of buying, or not buying, but clearing land, you know, and using the logs.
But it was not anything like it developed into, not 55 feet high.
Let's see.
What feelings do you hold in your heart for Texas A&M today?
All of these.
And I never get over that love for A&M, you know.
And as a matter of fact, after I finally got out of that graduation thing, I started to work out of A&M.
I knew the guy that
kept doors at the football games, and I knew that the other ones were basketball games.
And for years I worked with those things, maybe six or seven years.
I went out as a gatekeeper, baseball even one time, but they didn't pay enough to keep me involved in it.
But I was a gatekeeper at all three of those games, type games, football, basketball, and baseball.
Do you remember your graduation?
Well, as a matter of fact, we didn't have any ceremonies.
They paged, some of the authorities paged the 286 of us there, however many of them were seniors, to see whether or not we wanted a graduation ceremony.
Well, in the first place, it was a small corps of people, men.
In the second place, most of us were on up in years, and probably our families lived miles and miles away
It would be an inconvenience to bring them down for a graduation ceremony.
So they paged us to see how many of us wanted a graduation ceremony.
And marginally, none of us didn't want to go through it.
So we didn't have a graduation ceremony.
What was that?
If you were trying to summarize your gratitude to Texas A&M today, how would you express that?
Well, it'd be kind of hard to do, you know.
I support the student thing, you know, the ex-student thing.
Maybe that's one way that I do it.
Sometimes I don't stand in
a hundred bucks or whatever, you know, it is, but I think it's a very good organization.
And it's just an awful lot about A&M that you, it's under the skin, but you don't know how to put fingers on it.
Of course, I live off the campus right here.
And I, in my condition, I rarely ever get out on the campus.
I have worked, like I said, with the

organizations the athletic association thing i've known a lot of this the athletes and and the wally groff and you know that his staff i don't know and once in a while they'll prior to the football season they'll have the coaches out there you know everybody goes and meets the students and the
new athletes and all that sort of thing.
And I like that kind of deal.
It kind of ties you to the...
I no longer work the gates anymore, but Cargill does.
And he's got a thousand friends out there.
And this one family comes, they've been there all the years when I worked there.
The man and his wife, they had two daughters and a son.
And they still come in at that gate.
And they always ask about me.
And you learn to know a lot of people, you know, on that thing.
They'll be there this year and next year until they die.
And it's nice to know that you've made that kind of friends.
And they're Aggies.
And there's just a loyalty there and a relationship that's, you know, you don't expect that kind of thing from people outside.
And even your church, you know.
It's just there.
Who can explain it?
Let's quit with that.
That's a splendid ending.
